etymologies: mid 16th century; earliest use found in Andrew Borde (c1490–1549), physician and author. From classical Latin praenōmināt-, past participial stem of praenōmināre + -ed Compare earlier prenominate, and later prenominate

definitions: Named or specified in advance, aforementioned; especially nominated for an election, post, etc., beforehand. Chiefly US in later use.
